  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Pneumonic adenocarcinoma (P-ADC) is defined as a primary lung ADC with a radiological
      pneumonic presentation, usually referred to histologically as ADC with a mixed-invasive and
      BAC predominant subtype in the 2004 WHO classification. Surgery is the best therapy for
      resectable tumors since the effectiveness of chemotherapy is disappointing. In the advanced
      P-ADC diffuse/multifocal types of BAC, epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR) tyrosine
      kinase inhibitors (TKIs) (gefitinib and erlotinib) have shown promise, with some rapid,
      dramatic responses, possibly reflecting specific molecular differences from other non-small
      cell lung carcinomas.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      We therefore conducted a French multicentric phase II trial (IFCT 0401) to evaluate activity
      and tolerance of gefitinib (250 mg/day) administered as first line treatment in patients with
      non-resectable P-ADC.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
